hands_on_practices.solution:
The mineral absorption rate is proportional to the total exposed surface area with a uniform flux, so if $R$ denotes rate and $A$ denotes area, then $R=jA$ for some constant $j$. For the wild-type segment, $A_{\text{wt}}=A_{\text{root}}+N A_{\text{hair}}$, and for the mutant (no hairs), $A_{\text{mut}}=A_{\text{root}}$. The fractional reduction in rate is
$$
\frac{R_{\text{wt}}-R_{\text{mut}}}{R_{\text{wt}}}
=\frac{j(A_{\text{wt}}-A_{\text{mut}})}{jA_{\text{wt}}}
=\frac{N A_{\text{hair}}}{A_{\text{root}}+N A_{\text{hair}}}.
$$
Treating each as a cylinder and neglecting base-coverage on the root body as instructed, use lateral surface areas:
$$
A_{\text{root}}=2\pi r_{\text{root}}L,\quad A_{\text{hair}}=2\pi r_{\text{hair}}l_{\text{hair}}.
$$
Therefore,
$$
\frac{R_{\text{wt}}-R_{\text{mut}}}{R_{\text{wt}}}
=\frac{N(2\pi r_{\text{hair}}l_{\text{hair}})}{2\pi r_{\text{root}}L+N(2\pi r_{\text{hair}}l_{\text{hair}})}
=\frac{1}{1+\dfrac{2\pi r_{\text{root}}L}{N(2\pi r_{\text{hair}}l_{\text{hair}})}}
=\frac{1}{1+\dfrac{r_{\text{root}}L}{N r_{\text{hair}}l_{\text{hair}}}}.
$$
Insert the given values converted to meters: $L=1.00\times 10^{-2}$, $r_{\text{root}}=2.00\times 10^{-4}$, $l_{\text{hair}}=7.50\times 10^{-4}$, $r_{\text{hair}}=5.00\times 10^{-6}$, $N=3000$:
$$
\frac{r_{\text{root}}L}{N r_{\text{hair}}l_{\text{hair}}}
=\frac{(2.00\times 10^{-4})(1.00\times 10^{-2})}{3000\,(5.00\times 10^{-6})(7.50\times 10^{-4})}
=\frac{2.00\times 10^{-6}}{3000\times 3.75\times 10^{-9}}
=\frac{2.00\times 10^{-6}}{1.125\times 10^{-5}}
=\frac{2}{11.25}=\frac{8}{45}.
$$
Hence,
$$
\frac{R_{\text{wt}}-R_{\text{mut}}}{R_{\text{wt}}}
=\frac{1}{1+\dfrac{8}{45}}=\frac{1}{\dfrac{53}{45}}=\frac{45}{53}\approx 0.849056\ldots
$$
Rounded to three significant figures, the fractional reduction is $0.849$.
